A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
We have already mentioned, on several occasions, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
ČTú (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, as a result of the last step taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that the prices in Czech Republic remain so high, in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this case, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), who stated several times that in Czech there was no room for another operator, choruses with operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network seems to have a lot more chance (in fact, now it would only find very difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable decline in prices, to which the traditional operators had to respond as well.
However, even before the arrival of the party disturbances such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those that are heard today at home would be heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the Virtual Operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there's the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need a lot less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, free from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good boost.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operator of this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be able to walk also at home.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman for Vodafone, undoubtedly: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
More and more, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Czech, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in Chechnya, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project to success, but in Czech negotiations are not very encouraging.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our area," said in a telephone entertainment for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that the operators in Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The Novera GTS group, who would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer field, has not been hiding, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile, telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's spokesperson.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by complete silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificities of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with the statement of O2: "We have not currently registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to the completion of requests to obtain his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
That is what we believe is the most valuable contribution from the point of view of the clients.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
So how good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators can understand themselves as larvae in the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTU, when creating the U:fon, was that exerted by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from ČTú websites.
Today, however, the U:fon stands ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition in the mobile market has also been recently expanded by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would, and above all, submit it to high requirements."
But given the attitude of these mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disappointing.
However, it is not just the attitude of ČTú, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has unfortunately not the power to intervene in economic competition in Chechnya.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," stated in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
Such a statement would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than misleading.
Even more so, Kristián Chalupa adds: "To the outside, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices of mobile phone services."
However, pressing for an honest functioning of the market and lowering prices does not appear to be part of UOHS's interests.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question is, if this is really a chance, it arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline that is strictly the same as all service stations is probably due to the chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none of them have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools necessary for the opening up of the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTU, according to which telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts offer another view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at any time.
And the mobile operator quite logically has the monopoly on his network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators proceed visibly in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including the Novera GTS, mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility for ČTú is a fairly common turn in communications, by which UOHS washes its hands.
We have already met with this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act was not successful in expanding the powers of ČTU in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
The UOHS representatives must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the operation of a sort of virtual pseudo-operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only public in part.
In most cases, it is a matter of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, special mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally reach only elected ones.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company makes before the operator is a classic business customer, who controls a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you mentioned happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would consider and which could lead to a halt in our collaboration with the society in question," answered our question on this issue Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such activity will not reach the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, decides against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligable benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a percentage of negligible customers.
Moreover, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the way ordinary customers of mobile operators."
However, this is precisely what should seem strange to ČTU.
In addition, another question is asked at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that UOHS has relatively wide powers to reveal such activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators sometimes tried to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulators, in developed countries, were involved, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators deal with this issue in the form of a hot potato to be disposed of by transmitting it to a near target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the feeling that confusion in skills is more beneficial to them in these cases than profitable.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the cog.
If the coulisse information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be in motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS can hardly remain impassible from the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may cease to call more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly introduced the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek sees Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted Český rozhlas (Czech Public Radio), he chose to interpret the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good word, so that we understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
For the first time in 1834, Kde domov sang on the plates of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of seven national symbols even after the creation of the Independent Czech Republic.
