Sudanese Claimed a Referendum in the USA
The Swedes Germans in 1945 called for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Swedish Germans allegedly addressed the President of the USA with such a desire.
This results, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna collections.
Germans from Český Krumlov, in the letter, ask the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be truly sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, "People, whose fate of Šumava is at heart."
Since the rally to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the US president to take into his hands the protection of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has not contributed in any way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of millions of inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text in the letter can, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Swedes Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least observe that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Great Britain would achieve a certain type of autonomy for the Sudan.
Others believed that they would just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms it.
During the war, it was, as German of Česke Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic countries.
When he was captured by the English at the end of the war and placed in the catch camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed, according to him, that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
