Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach escapes in the face of danger, does that mean he feels too afraid?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of the answers to the question "What do you think is true without having proof?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else until now being able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains present the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and deal with the questions of feeling or in general consciousness, we will enter into areas that are difficult to practice because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it makes death, escapes or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduct a comparable subjective life.
However, I don't believe in it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective life to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and leadership and enforcement functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
So at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the Prefrontal Cortex, including the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from the other primates.
Another significant characteristic could be the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on him.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if conscience did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our consciences.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what the consciousness of other animals may look like.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, as a result of this particular Hardware, to analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses serious problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious life, but there is another aspect of the consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
