"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no outer garments.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in the intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who do not care to go on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatre of some staging with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the specific iconography of flamenco in different angles.
Including in the programming of Flamenco Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, more every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivated the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a clean personality and character.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of flamenco stars."
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph the singers, guitarists or dancers with a flat-screen camera.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the material, reminisce the classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dancing or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic was the constant of this work that is being presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
The flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter into their lives for a moment or less.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult kind.
You're in front of people, people that sometimes you don't know or leave you just a few minutes to get a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try that my ideas become reality."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco called "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at the number 20 of the rue de la Mata (road parallel to the People's of Hercules) which will be opened until 16 October next.
