I do not refer to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder that's called sleepwalking.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
It's sure there's more than one talking during the night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of severe fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (pipi-bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very strong fever, stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it's a poorly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with screams, cries, long speeches ...
If sleeping becomes very frequent, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check whether there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a benign alteration, so there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is related to a sleep apnea or stress).
What we can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid television shows or programs that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as sleepwalks appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because he's sleeping in it, he's not aware to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, suddenly watch out for the way you interpret the information and conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can ask him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
