Interview - Blood came back safe
Hema-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Dr. Francine Decary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec became one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the public, the Government of Canada in February 1994 instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to cease to occur.
While Judge Krever was slow to file his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan for a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and two territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec started his activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Decary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
In an effort to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had now trusted in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, has to bear in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
From its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which has been holding the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when one does not know about it and a serious disease may result, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had been living in the United Kingdom for more than a month had been refused since 1980.
A few years ago, however, it was demonstrated beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle applied was meaningful."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that directly detect the presence of the virus itself and not antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The NTAs shorten the silent period, which extends between the moment the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could have been reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors are infected without knowing and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
Not later that last year appeared on Réunion Island the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continued before pointing out that in addition to a security supply, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors who on average group only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any person aged 18 and over who is in health can still give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who offer their blood are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is plagued, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But members of this donor network must be renewed as they get older and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so frightful, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye and skin globes that are almost exclusively used for large burned people.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cordon blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and are expected to take more than a thousand per year.
It should begin to be proposed for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary who describes this cordon blood sampling program as very popular.
"More mothers are disappointed that they can't have access to it", because Hema-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
