If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defence and to fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
Tactical, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will ban the opposition in addition to frighten anyone who dares to reconsider the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are normally conducted by exchanging ideas and not by beatings.
It was therefore enough for the mining industry to open its books, dossiers and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada from the back of his hand.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he could at the same time ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the opinions of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to paid and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even the detractors have the right to speak.
What does not understand - or doesn't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This public is willing to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a barbarian prosecution (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a settlement at the place of the authors of Black Canada who are trying to stop the use of this term...).
Beyond Mr Garver's surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in a block, the right to quote credible sources and the debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease rich businesses in this world in a country like Canada, under repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The academic environment, which we belong to, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The ongoing pursuit of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to her claim, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices limiting this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by the two Houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides: better control by the elected members of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of consideration on wages paid to the managers of the assisted enterprises.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis at Wall Street," the democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to the sprinkling in the last few hours because of the impact that would cause a further failure on investors' mood.
The deadline was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their discontent that they were forced to reach this end.
The Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that to allow owners to keep their homes and the salary of the managers of the state-run enterprises.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked about another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the suspicious, active and inventable claims of US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the burst of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprime) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had brought together the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this deadlock since the Democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its implementation.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to be added to another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be endorsed by another Congress vote.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will obtain participation in the assisted companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment is passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the procedures for seizures of housing related to the real estate loans involved in this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and severance allowances paid to the managers of affected enterprises.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and to the House of Representatives on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
In fact, votes continued yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Of course, Washington doesn't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, member of the House's Finance Committee.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, have written us to tell us: we are asking Congress not to press and carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we had once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (US 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas had indicated that it had refused to acquire its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost EUR 2 billion (US 2.9 billion) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said the Dutch Minister of Finance yesterday, Wouter Bos.
In return, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are telling themselves uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank damaged by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take into account all current loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would purchase the branches and accounts of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
