On 8 October, hearings will begin in connection with the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, permanently and on a regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage, and other charges have been held against them, such as false and false.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and the municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand to the banks of the Fiatal Balldal movement and on the other hand, to the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to pay the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices of fees, behind which no actual benefits were provided and thus, associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they were looking for invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the caches in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were to be included on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the northern tours of Lake Balaton, made by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's statement, he was required to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on which model they made the other invoices they were going to introduce, inter alia, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of Capital for access to grants.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his partner András, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with writing the files needed to obtain the subsidies.
During a "research circuit", one of Lados' choice was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
In the same way, in the summer of 2002, the invoice established on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will subsequently be known as Együtt a Harmadik Évesredert, ransacked of faults of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the invoice mentioned 100 customers.
