The psychology of over-heating: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
The New York University's neurology and economic researchers have been able to update the neurological and economic basis for this apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as auction sales on eBay, and that is why they prefer even to pay too high a price.
These researches attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging process (MRI), researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction sale, a key element of which is the over auction of a third, the whole of which was under the brain stem, called striatum, was placed in intensive motion during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight to the violent reaction of striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
At the same time, three groups were overindulging against a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus carried out their assessment.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the party, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, if they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the focus was on victory, while the other was on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the player team "against failure" were willing to put higher than those performed by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena found during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurologic imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, now resulting in a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York, found.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that the diseased carriers of the hepatitis virus in Hungary are estimated to be 100 miles, but only seven miles are being treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are carrying the virus.
Hepatitis name is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowish are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, propagate mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is recommended in any way. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, in general, accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach disease and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white eye a visible yellow, the soles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die of the most severe form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogen gene destroys the liver cells in a sneezing way. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had suffered from a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis are found worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor who treats you as soon as you observe symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, first organized in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick from around the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows up in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article that researchers at Oxford University had an interesting experience analyzing how belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of human beings.
As part of this experience for the least odd, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, with academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participating from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and spreading electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings in a sustained manner, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady to Hermine painted by Léonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was concerned with its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time they received 20 electroshocks in four succeeding parts, while looking at either the religious theme painting or the more general theme one.
Catholics said that in the eyes of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", as someone who "takes care" and they "quieted, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of a religious theme, they reported 12% of pain in less than when they looked at Léonard's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image in front of which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases, it does change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, is there no longer the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of subject pain if believers were to show a Madonna painted by Léonard or a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a better quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
