Smart car imitates bourdon's flight
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
Like, for example, the bees' one.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bourdonating bees gave the strategic idea of departure to the engineers of Nissan, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotized control system, type BR23C, that he equipped bees' qualities, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system that can avoid all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval form, which actually resembles a lot of our secure protective hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The bee facet eye plays an essential role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the facet eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, assesses the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle enough to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is carried out entirely instinctively.
"If that wasn't the case, the mini robot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," says Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, it was only possible to use the rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is higher, making their life span longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive smart reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the capacity to store.
This mechanism should treat only a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of memory continuously.
There is no need for memory of a giga-bytes capacity, not even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. Nissan's estimates show that this system will make its entry into the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
