Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - the Central Office for Statistics in Hungary reports.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those in the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to those in the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1%, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only a small increase in the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of chemicals (1.6 per cent).
Deflation resulted in oil processing (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry increased from 0.2% to 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which are important in national industrial operations, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a comparison of 12 months, taking into account the domestic sale of the processing sectors, the most significant increase in the oil processing sector was the price of 32.4 per cent.
In the metal manufacturing sector, a 13.2 per cent increase in prices was observed, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions were made in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases have increased from 0.6% to 9.1%.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, the investment profit-initiating sectors showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials sectors for subsequent processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent processing (16.8 per cent) was observed.
In the consumer goods sector, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while for the benefit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 per cent decrease was recorded.
The export prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment decreased by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and 7.1 percent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
