Listen to full-volume music for an extended period using portable music devices such as MP3 players, can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a communiqué in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unanticipated and recently identified health risks (Csserri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific- lisons report we in the note- it is clear that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and week, risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such an important number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data - the EU leader continues - it is a clear risk and we need to respond quickly.
What is most important is to raise awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in view of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can monitor new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young noise exposures they generate.
"Scientists-conclude the Executive EU- confirm that there are good reasons to be alarmed, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures might possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents, against noise exposure from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but concern increases as to the auditory damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to properly limit these data using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum permitted noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions over extended periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to approximately 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
