In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the phenomena covered for some time, so much so that in the new climate they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-upgrading, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of the sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with the foreign country, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is to say how to respond to the difficulties and protests of the people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of play, or has little to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, shared as usual, among the various interests and among the various national strategies, does not succeed in deciding any common political lines.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit condition: when we go through a difficult period, there is only the States that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimization to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements of which no market or international organization can ever have in a similar manner.
This new emphasis on the state-nation crisis is, of course, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the most recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future would, on the contrary, have to settle more and more with the rather little material things such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territorial, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved to be inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And also, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
This increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their height, their listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, having the same time, and being increasingly foreign to the opinions of the majority.
