The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the large Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of province,
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multirooms, and the death of consumption of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inescapable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and charged with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a end of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Heavenly Cinema, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes Jury, and who told the poetry of a province hall, and nostalgia in a way of living the movie, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trading association, mean everything: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the halls of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine has 82 cinemas mono halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the past five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has grown irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still ensure the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these people are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of discussion of credit for traders: the former debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million a year.
Let us note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono halls of the historic and periphery centres.
The planned regulations include tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and special rates will be available for parking and in certain parking spaces.
"It's an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
However, it is clear that, to contrast the superpower of multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
